{"cursor":"30932","size":15,"audio":[],"currentlang":"en","article":"\n\n\n\n'' honors the first 100 years of peace between Great Britain and the United\nStates resulting from the signing of the Treaty of Ghent in 1814.]] , one of\nseveral symbols used to represent peace]]\n\n'Peace' is a state of harmony characterized by the lack of violent, conflict\nbehaviours and the freedom from fear of violence. Commonly understood as the\nabsence of hostility, peace also suggests the existence of healthy or newly\nhealed interpersonal or international relationships, prosperity in matters of\nsocial or economic welfare, the establishment of equality, and a working\npolitical order that serves the true interests of all. In international\nrelations, peacetime is not only the absence of war or violent conflict, but\nalso the presence of positive and respectful cultural and economic\nrelationships.\n","linknr":723,"url":"Peace","recorded":1362534943,"links":147,"instances":["people"],"pdf":["http://files.rhodes.gethifi.com/Ottawa_September_2011_To_render_war_impossible.pdf","http://www.politics.ox.ac.uk/materials/news/Fulbright_18May12_Arndt.pdf"],"categories":["Peace|","Core issues in ethics","Nonviolence","Pacifism","Ethical principles","Social concepts"],"headings":["Etymology","Religious beliefs and peace {{anchor|Religion}}","Justice and injustice","Movements and activism","Monuments","Theories","Peace and conflict studies","Measuring and Ranking Peace","See also","Notes","References","External links",""],"image":["//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/en/thumb/9/99/Question_book-new.svg/50px-Question_book-new.svg.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/e/e8/Crystal_Clear_app_kedit.svg/40px-Crystal_Clear_app_kedit.svg.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/a/ae/Fountain_of_Time_full_front.jpg/280px-Fountain_of_Time_full_front.jpg","//bits.wikimedia.org/static-1.21wmf10/skins/common/images/magnify-clip.png","//upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/thumb/